Let us consider this problem. Six points are placed evenly around a circle, like stars in the sky. We choose three of these points to form a triangle, but this triangle is not like the others – it has sides of different lengths.

Imagine drawing lines from the center of the circle to each of the points. This divides our triangle into smaller, equal triangles. Each of these smaller triangles is like a slice of a pie, and they are all the same size.

Now, if we connect every other point on the circle, we get a triangle that is perfectly balanced – all its sides are the same length. This is a special triangle called an equilateral triangle.

We know the radius of the circle is 1, which means each side of this equilateral triangle is also 1.  We can use this to find the area of the equilateral triangle.

The area of an equilateral triangle is (√3/4) times the square of its side length. So, the area of this equilateral triangle is (√3/4) * 1² = √3/4.

Our desired triangle is formed by taking away one of these smaller equilateral triangles from the larger one. Therefore, its area is (√3/4) - (√3/16) = (3√3)/16.



